\title{Scrivener}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{version}{1.0.0}

\meta{description}{Scrivener project format internals, data model, and programmatic access. Use when parsing .scriv bundles, querying DuckDB exports, extracting manuscript text, or building AI-assisted novel tools from Scrivener data. Covers Windows-origin projects, cross-platform migration, and RTF content.}

\subtree{
\title{Scrivener: Project Format, Data Model & Programmatic Access}
\p{\strong{Trit}: -1 (MINUS - validator/extractor) \strong{Color}: #E91A2F (Character Notes red)}

\subtree{
\title{When to use this skill}
\ul{
\li{Parsing or inspecting \code{.scriv} project bundles (XML, RTF, metadata)}
\li{Querying a DuckDB export of Scrivener data (documents, content, labels)}
\li{Extracting manuscript text, character info, or synopses programmatically}
\li{Migrating projects across Scrivener versions or platforms (Windows ↔ macOS)}
\li{Building tools that read/write Scrivener project structures}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{File Format: .scriv Bundle}
\p{A \code{.scriv} project is a directory. On macOS it displays as a single file (document package); on Windows it's a regular folder.}

\pre{\startverb
MyProject.scriv/
├── Files/
│   ├── Data/
│   │   ├── <UUID>/
│   │   │   ├── content.rtf       # Document body (RTF format)
│   │   │   ├── notes.rtf         # Inspector notes (RTF)
│   │   │   ├── synopsis.txt      # Synopsis text
│   │   │   └── snapshot-*.rtf    # Version snapshots
│   │   └── docs.checksum         # Integrity checksums
│   ├── binder.autosave           # Auto-saved binder state
│   ├── binder.backup             # Binder backup
│   ├── search.indexes            # Full-text search index
│   ├── styles.xml                # Document styles
│   ├── version.txt               # Format version
│   └── writing.history           # Session word counts
├── <ProjectName>.scrivx           # Master XML: binder tree + metadata
├── Settings/
│   ├── recents.txt               # Recent documents
│   ├── ui-common.xml             # Cross-platform UI state
│   └── ui.ini                    # Platform-specific UI state
└── QuickLook/
    └── Preview.html              # Finder preview (macOS only)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Version History & Cross-Platform Migration}
\p{The ☼ project was \strong{created on Windows} and has been migrated through multiple Scrivener versions:}

\pre{\startverb
| Version | Platform | Format | Notes |
|---------|----------|--------|-------|
| Scrivener 1 (Win) | Windows | XML `.scrivx` v1 + RTF | Original Windows port. `.scriv` is a visible folder. |
| Scrivener 1 (Mac) | macOS | Binary plist `.scrivproj` + RTF | macOS only, different format entirely. |
| Scrivener 2 (Mac) | macOS | Binary plist → XML | Transitional. No Windows v2 existed. |
| Scrivener 3 (Win) | Windows | XML `.scrivx` v2 + RTF | **Current**. Creator tag: `SCRWIN-3.x.x.x` |
| Scrivener 3 (Mac) | macOS | XML `.scrivx` v2 + RTF | **Current**. Creator tag: `SCRMAC-3.x.x` |
\stopverb}

\subtree{
\title{Windows → macOS migration}
\ul{
\li{\code{.scriv} folder on Windows is a regular directory; on macOS it becomes a document package (UTI: \code{com.literatureandlatte.scrivener3.scriv})}
\li{Copy the entire \code{.scriv} folder to macOS and open with Scrivener 3 — it auto-upgrades}
\li{The \code{Creator} attribute in \code{.scrivx} preserves origin: \code{SCRWIN-3.1.5.1} means Windows Scrivener 3.1.5.1}
\li{\code{ui.ini} stores platform-specific UI state; \code{ui-common.xml} stores cross-platform state}
\li{QuickLook/ only generated on macOS}
\li{Line endings in RTF may differ (CRLF from Windows, LF on macOS) — both parse correctly}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Version upgrade path}
\p{Windows v1 → Windows v3: Scrivener auto-converts on open. Creates backup of v1 project first. Binder structure, labels, statuses, and content preserved. Custom metadata fields may need manual re-setup.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{.scrivx XML Schema}
\p{The \code{.scrivx} file is the master index:}

\pre{\startverb
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<ScrivenerProject Template="No" Version="2.0"
    Identifier="UUID" Creator="SCRWIN-3.1.5.1"
    Device="HOSTNAME" Modified="2025-03-14 22:15:28 -0600"
    ModID="UUID">
  <Binder>
    <BinderItem UUID="..." Type="DraftFolder" Created="..." Modified="...">
      <Title>Draft</Title>
      <MetaData>
        <IncludeInCompile>Yes</IncludeInCompile>
      </MetaData>
      <Children>
        <BinderItem UUID="..." Type="Text" Created="..." Modified="...">
          <Title>Chapter 1</Title>
          <MetaData>
            <LabelID>2</LabelID>
            <StatusID>-1</StatusID>
            <IncludeInCompile>Yes</IncludeInCompile>
            <SectionType>-1</SectionType>
          </MetaData>
        </BinderItem>
      </Children>
    </BinderItem>
  </Binder>
  <LabelSettings>
    <Labels>
      <Label ID="0" Color="0.993 0.227 0.172">Red</Label>
    </Labels>
  </LabelSettings>
  <StatusSettings>
    <StatusItems>
      <Status ID="1">To Do</Status>
      <Status ID="2">In Progress</Status>
      <Status ID="3">First Draft</Status>
    </StatusItems>
  </StatusSettings>
  <ProjectProperties>
    <ProjectTitle>My Novel</ProjectTitle>
    <FullName>Author Name</FullName>
  </ProjectProperties>
</ScrivenerProject>
\stopverb}

\subtree{
\title{BinderItem Types}
\pre{\startverb
| Type | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `DraftFolder` | Manuscript root (compile target) |
| `ResearchFolder` | Research materials container |
| `TrashFolder` | Deleted items |
| `Folder` | User-created folder |
| `Text` | Document (main content unit) |
| `PDF` | Imported PDF |
| `Image` | Imported image |
| `WebArchive` | Saved web page |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Document Content Storage}
\p{Each document's UUID maps to \code{Files/Data/<UUID>/}:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{content.rtf}: Body text. Contains inline annotations via \code{\{\Scrv_fn=...\}} custom tags.}
\li{\strong{notes.rtf}: Inspector notes pane.}
\li{\strong{synopsis.txt}: Plain text synopsis (corkboard cards).}
\li{\strong{snapshot-YYYY-MM-DD-HH-MM-SS.rtf}: Version snapshots.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Color Values}
\p{Colors in \code{.scrivx} are space-separated RGB floats (0.0–1.0):}

\pre{\startverb
# "0.952941 0.917647 0.329412" → #F3EB54
hex_color = f"#{int(r*255):02x}{int(g*255):02x}{int(b*255):02x}"
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{DuckDB Export Schema}
\p{When exported to DuckDB (via \code{build_sun_org.py} or similar):}

\subtree{
\title{\code{documents}}
\pre{\startverb
CREATE TABLE documents (
    project VARCHAR,          -- e.g. '☼'
    uuid VARCHAR PRIMARY KEY,
    title VARCHAR,
    parent_uuid VARCHAR,
    depth_int INT,            -- Nesting depth in binder
    item_type VARCHAR,        -- 'Text', 'Folder', etc.
    label_id INT,
    status_id INT,
    include_in_compile VARCHAR,
    binder_id VARCHAR,        -- Binder sort order
    section_type INT
);
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{\code{content}}
\pre{\startverb
CREATE TABLE content (
    project VARCHAR,
    uuid VARCHAR,             -- FK to documents
    body TEXT,                -- Full RTF body
    synopsis TEXT,
    notes TEXT,
    body_length INT,
    content_file_type VARCHAR
);
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{\code{labels}, \code{statuses}, \code{comments}}
\pre{\startverb
CREATE TABLE labels (project VARCHAR, label_id INT, name VARCHAR, color VARCHAR);
CREATE TABLE statuses (project VARCHAR, status_id INT, name VARCHAR);
CREATE TABLE comments (project VARCHAR, uuid VARCHAR, comment_text TEXT, position INT);
\stopverb}

\p{Additional tables: \code{collections}, \code{bookmarks}, \code{styles}, \code{section_types}, \code{projects}.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Queries}
\subtree{
\title{Manuscript text in binder order}
\pre{\startverb
SELECT d.uuid, d.title, c.body, c.synopsis
FROM documents d
JOIN content c ON d.uuid = c.uuid AND d.project = c.project
WHERE d.project = '☼'
  AND d.item_type = 'Text'
  AND d.include_in_compile = 'Yes'
  AND c.body IS NOT NULL
ORDER BY d.binder_id;
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Find documents mentioning a character}
\pre{\startverb
SELECT d.uuid, d.title, d.binder_id, length(c.body) AS bodylen
FROM documents d
JOIN content c ON d.uuid = c.uuid AND d.project = c.project
WHERE d.project = '☼' AND c.body ILIKE '%edith%'
ORDER BY d.binder_id;
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Strip Scrivener RTF tags}
\pre{\startverb
import re
clean = re.sub(r'\{\\Scrv_fn=.*?\\end_Scrv_fn\}', '', body)
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{RTF Content Notes}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Inline annotations}: \code{\{\Scrv_fn=footnote ...text... \end_Scrv_fn\}}}
\li{\strong{Comments}: Stored in \code{comments} table with position offsets}
\li{\strong{Styles}: Referenced by name from \code{styles.xml}}
\li{\strong{Images}: Embedded as RTF \code{\pict} objects or referenced externally}
\li{\strong{Links}: Internal links use \code{scrivener://} protocol with UUID targets}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Character Data Extraction}
\p{Scrivener fiction templates include a Characters folder with sketch documents (Role, Occupation, Physical Description, etc.) — but these are \strong{plain RTF}, not structured data. In the ☼ project, the Characters folder contains only a blank template.}

\p{Characters must be detected from prose:}

\pre{\startverb
import duckdb

con = duckdb.connect('scrivener.duckdb', read_only=True)

def character_chunks(char_name: str) -> list:
    return con.execute("""
        SELECT d.title, left(c.body, 500) as preview, d.binder_id
        FROM documents d
        JOIN content c ON d.uuid = c.uuid AND d.project = c.project
        WHERE d.project = '☼'
          AND c.body ILIKE ?
          AND length(c.body) > 50
        ORDER BY d.binder_id
    """, [f'%{char_name}%']).fetchall()

# ☼ characters: she, narrator, ack, edith, deb, rad, glen, will, hub
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{macOS vs Windows Differences}
\pre{\startverb
| Aspect | macOS | Windows |
|--------|-------|---------|
| `.scriv` appearance | Document package (single file) | Regular folder |
| Browse internals | Right-click → Show Package Contents | Open folder normally |
| UTI | `com.literatureandlatte.scrivener3.scriv` | N/A |
| QuickLook preview | Generated automatically | Not available |
| Spotlight indexing | Via `mdls` metadata | Windows Search indexes RTF |
| Line endings in RTF | LF | CRLF |
| Creator tag | `SCRMAC-3.x.x` | `SCRWIN-3.x.x.x` |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Verify it worked}
\p{After parsing a \code{.scriv} project:}

\ol{
\li{Check that the \code{.scrivx} XML parses and contains \code{<Binder>} with at least one \code{<BinderItem>}}
\li{Verify UUID directories exist under \code{Files/Data/} for documents listed in the binder}
\li{Confirm \code{content.rtf} files are valid RTF (start with \code{\{\rtf1})}
\li{If using DuckDB export: \code{SELECT count(*) FROM documents} should match binder item count}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{What not to do}
\ul{
\li{Don't modify \code{.scriv} files while Scrivener has the project open — it uses file locks}
\li{Don't assume synopsis or notes fields are populated — many projects leave them empty}
\li{Don't parse RTF with regex for anything beyond stripping Scrivener tags — use a real RTF parser for styled content}
\li{Don't assume macOS package structure on Windows — \code{.scriv} is just a folder there}
\li{Don't delete \code{docs.checksum} — Scrivener uses it for integrity verification on open}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{☼ Project Specifics}
\ul{
\li{\strong{949 documents}: 900 Text, 42 Folders, 2 PDF, 2 Image}
\li{\strong{432 manuscript chunks} with body > 50 chars}
\li{\strong{Labels}: Idea (#F3EB54), Chapter (#48B300), Scene (#468EFF), Notes (#E48738), Character Notes (#E91A2F)}
\li{\strong{Characters folder}: Only a blank template (unfilled)}
\li{\strong{No synopsis metadata} (1 boilerplate entry on Title Page)}
\li{\strong{2 inline comments}: Both authorial reminders}
\li{\strong{Origin}: Created on Windows Scrivener, migrated through version updates}
}
}

